\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Linear Analysis Homework 9
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Michael Nelson
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this homework, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a separable Hilbert space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a compact positive self-adjoint operator.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T=|T|$
\end_inset

, and consequently the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 coincide with the singular values of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Choose an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $(e_{n})$
\end_inset

 consisting of distinct eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Te_{n}=\lambda_{n}e_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 (this exists since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is compact and self-adjoint).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(e_{n})$
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal basis consisting of eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}=T^{*}T$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}e_{n}=\lambda_{n}^{2}e_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is positive and self-adjoint), we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|T|x & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}s_{n}\langle x,e_{n}\rangle e_{n}\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\sqrt{\lambda_{n}^{2}}\langle x,e_{n}\rangle e_{n}\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\lambda_{n}\langle x,e_{n}\rangle e_{n}\\
 & =Tx
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $T=|T|$
\end_inset

, and consequently 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{n}=\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(e_{n})$
\end_inset

 be an orthonormal basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T(x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}\langle x,e_{n}\rangle e_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 is compact but not Hilbert-Schmidt.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For this problem, I decided to prove this in an arbitrary separable Hilbert
 space than just 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell^{2}(\mathbb{N})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, define 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{k}(x)=\sum_{n=1}^{k}\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}\langle x,e_{n}\rangle e_{n}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

.
 First note that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{k}$
\end_inset

 is bounded and has finite rank, and hence must be compact.
 Moreover, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T-T_{k}\|\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $k\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B_{1}[0]$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}|\langle x,e_{n}\rangle|^{2}\leq1$
\end_inset

).
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $K\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1/K<\varepsilon.$
\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq K$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|Tx-T_{k}x\|^{2} & =\left\Vert \sum_{n=k+1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}\langle x,e_{n}\rangle e_{n}\right\Vert ^{2}\\
 & =\sum_{n=k+1}^{\infty}\left|\frac{\langle x,e_{n}\rangle}{\sqrt{n}}\right|^{2}\\
 & =\sum_{n=k+1}^{\infty}\frac{|\langle x,e_{n}\rangle|^{2}}{n}\\
 & \leq\frac{1}{K}\sum_{n=k+1}^{\infty}|\langle x,e_{n}\rangle|^{2}\\
 & \leq\frac{1}{K}\\
 & <\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T-T_{k}\|\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $k\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(T_{k})$
\end_inset

 is a sequence of compact operators such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T-T_{k}\|\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $k\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is compact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is not Hilbert-Schmidt, observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\|Te_{n}\|^{2} & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\|\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}e_{n}\|^{2}\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

is the harmonic series which does not converge.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3.a
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propeigenvaluebound}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a self-adjoint operator and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 be an eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $|\lambda|\leq\|T\|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Choose an eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 By scaling if necessary, we may assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|T\| & =\sup\{|\langle Ty,y\rangle|\mid\|y\|\leq1\}\\
 & \geq|\langle Tx,x\rangle|\\
 & =|\langle\lambda x,x\rangle|\\
 & =|\lambda|.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3.b
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmanormmodulus}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a compact operator.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\||T|\|=\|T\|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Combining problem 5 on HW5 and problem 6.b on HW6, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\||T|\|^{2} & =\||T|^{2}\|\\
 & =\|T^{*}T\|\\
 & =\|T\|^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\||T|\|=\|T\|$
\end_inset

 since the norm of an operator is nonnegative.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a compact operator and let 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 be a singular value of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq s\leq\|T\|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Clearly we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s\geq0$
\end_inset

 by definition.
 Combining 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmanormmodulus})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propeigenvaluebound})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|s| & \leq\||T|\|\\
 & =\|T\|.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3.c
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a compact operator.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{n})$
\end_inset

 be the sequence of singular values of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T\|_{\text{HS}}=\sqrt{\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}s_{n}^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 be an orthonormal basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}T$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|T\|_{\text{HS}} & =\sqrt{\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\|Tx_{n}\|^{2}}\\
 & =\sqrt{\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\langle Tx_{n},Tx_{n}\rangle}\\
 & =\sqrt{\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\langle T^{*}Tx_{n},x_{n}\rangle}\\
 & =\sqrt{\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\langle s_{n}^{2}x_{n},x_{n}\rangle}\\
 & =\sqrt{\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}s_{n}^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a compact self-adjoint operator.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}+T+1$
\end_inset

 cannot be the zero operator.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{n})$
\end_inset

 be the sequence of eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $(e_{n})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the sequence of eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}+T+1=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then by the spectral theorem, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =(T^{2}+T+1)e_{n}\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}(\lambda_{n}^{2}+\lambda_{n}+1)\langle e_{n},e_{n}\rangle e_{n}\\
 & =(\lambda_{n}^{2}+\lambda_{n}+1)e_{n},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}^{2}+\lambda_{n}+1=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}=\pm e^{2\pi i/3}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, but this contradicts the fact that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

 must be real.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 5
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 be a compact operator.
 Then there exists a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{n}\colon\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 of operators with finite dimensional range such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T_{n}-T\|\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T=U|T|$
\end_inset

 be the polar decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(|T_{m}|)$
\end_inset

 of operators with finite dimensional range such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\||T_{m}|-|T|\|\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $m\to\infty$
\end_inset

 (such a sequence exists by problem 6 HW8).
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $U|T_{m}|$
\end_inset

 has finite dimensional range since 
\begin_inset Formula $|T_{m}|$
\end_inset

 has finite dimensional range.
 Moreover we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T-U|T_{m}|\|\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $m\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq M$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\||T|-|T_{m}|\|<\varepsilon/\|U\|$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq M$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|T-U|T_{m}|\| & =\|U|T|-U|T_{m}|\|\\
 & =\|U\|\||T|-|T_{m}|\|\\
 & <\|U\|\frac{\varepsilon}{\|U\|}\\
 & =\varepsilon.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

